GA Data Science Final Project

Land Cover Classification with Sklearn
by Anastasia Clark
Problem Definition

Land cover refers to the surface cover on the ground, whether vegetation, urban infrastructure, water, bare soil or other. Land cover maps are used primarily for land use planning, bur also increasingly for climate modeling

Some of the land use applications include:
  • natural resource management
  • wildlife habitat protection
  • baseline mapping for GIS input
  • urban expansion / encroachment
  • legal boundaries for tax and property evaluation
Problem Statement

Perform land cover classification using Sentinel 2 data and Sklearn algorithms learned in class.

Land Cover Map Portland, Oregon

Data Preprocessing
In [34]:
def crop_band(clip_gdf, input_folder, band, output_folder, out_name):
    if not os.path.exists(output_folder):
        os.makedirs(output_folder)
    crop_feature = [json.loads(clip_gdf.to_json())['features'][0]['geometry']]    
    src=rasterio.open(os.path.join(input_folder, band))
    out_image, out_transform=mask(src, crop_feature, crop=True)
    out_meta=src.meta.copy()
    out_meta.update({'height': out_image.shape[1],
                   'width':out_image.shape[2],
                   'transform': out_transform})

    with rasterio.open(f'{output_folder}/{out_name}.tif', 'w', **out_meta) as dest:
        dest.write(out_image)
  • Orinal bands are 5490 pixels wide and 5490 pixels tall
  • Resulted clipped bands have 537 rows and 682 columns
Feature generation to add additional dimension

Normalized Difference Vegetation Index (NDVI) quantifies vegetation by measuring the difference between near-infrared (which vegetation strongly reflects) and red light (which vegetation absorbs). NDVI always ranges from -1 to +1. But there isnt a distinct boundary for each type of land cover.

For example, when you have negative values, its highly likely that its water.

On the other hand, if you have a NDVI value close to +1, theres a high possibility that its dense green leaves.

But when NDVI is close to zero, there isnt green leaves and it could even be an urbanized area.

https://gisgeography.com/ndvi-normalized-difference-vegetation-index/

$NDVI=\frac{NIR-RED}{NIR+RED}$

In [39]:
# write the function to calculate NDVI
def calculate_ndvi(red, nir):
    ''' Given Red and NIR bands as input, 
    calcuates NDVI'''
    
    # beacase division will unlikely result in integers
    # change the datatype of our arrays from integer to float
    red=red.astype(float)
    nir=nir.astype(float)
    
    # since we have 0 values
    # we need to mask them out, so that they don't participate in the calculations
    masked_red=np.ma.masked_where(red==0, red)
    masked_nir=np.ma.masked_where(nir==0, nir)
    
    # NDVI formula
    ndvi=(masked_nir-masked_red)/(masked_nir+masked_red)
    ndvi=ndvi.filled(fill_value=-1)
    return ndvi

Limitations and Future Work
  • Model will not be abble to predict classes it hasn't been trained on
  • Additional data with images around different geographical areas and different seasons will make the model more robust
  • Adding additinal bands and features (ex: NDWI and NDSI) will help with distinguishing other closely-related land cover classes
